<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-167-046 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 620 811</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  May 1991 v9 n5 p108(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Windows scanner comes easily to hand. (Nisca Inc.'s Niscan/GSscanner for Microsoft Windows) (Hardware Review) (Product Outlook)(evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hogan, Mike.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Nisca Inc manufactures four types of hand scanners: the $369Niscan/GS and the $399 Niscan/GS for Microsoft Windows 3.0 bothoffer 8-bit image scanning in 265 shades of gray.andP;  For an extra$200, Nisca throws in optical character recognition (OCR)enhancing software.andP;  The Niscan/GS OCR sells for $569, while theNiscan/GS OCR for Windows costs $599.andP;  The Niscan/GS scannersallow resolution movement from 25 to 400 dots per inch.andP;  GEM-basedScanXpress software for pre-scan controls and post-scan imageediting is used for non-Windows models.andP;  Windows models useImage-In's Scanandamp;Paint scan-control and paint program andImage-In's Plus post-scan gray-scale editor.andP;  Upgrades areavailable from Niscan/GS to Niscan/GS for Windows for $49 and fromNiscan/GS OCR to Niscan/GS OCR for Windows for $149.andP;  Users whohave a previous version of Niscan/GS OCR for Windows withImage-In's Read can upgrade to Perceive Personal for $49.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   NISCA Inc. (Products).andO;Product:   Niscan/GS (Scanning device)Niscan/GS OCR (Scanning device).andO;Topic:     EvaluationScanning Devices.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Company information and evaluation summary. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>